# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: secure-coding-practices
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] In software engineering, **code coverage**, also called **test coverage**, is a percentage measure of the degree to which the source code of a program is executed when a particular test suite is run.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] A program with high code coverage has more of its source code executed during testing, which suggests it has a lower chance of containing undetected software bugs compared to a program with low code coverage.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Many different metrics can be used to calculate test coverage.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Some of the most basic are the percentage of program subroutines and the percentage of program statements called during execution of the test suite.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Code coverage was among the first methods invented for systematic software testing.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] The first published reference was by Miller and Maloney in *Communications of the ACM*, in 1963.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] To measure what percentage of code has been executed by a test suite, one or more *coverage criteria* are used.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] These are usually defined as rules or requirements, which a test suite must satisfy.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Assume this function is a part of some bigger program and this program was run with some test suite.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] In programming languages that do not perform short-circuit evaluation, condition coverage does not necessarily imply branch coverage.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] However, this set of tests does not satisfy branch coverage since neither case will meet the `if` condition.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Fault injection may be necessary to ensure that all conditions and branches of exception-handling code have adequate coverage during testing.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] A combination of function coverage and branch coverage is sometimes also called **decision coverage**.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] This criterion requires that every point of entry and exit in the program has been invoked at least once, and every decision in the program has taken on all possible outcomes at least once.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] In this context, the decision is a Boolean expression comprising conditions and zero or more Boolean operators.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] This definition is not the same as branch coverage, however, the term *decision coverage* is sometimes used as a synonym for it.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] However, the above tests set will not satisfy modified condition/decision coverage, since in the first test, the value of 'b' and in the second test the value of 'c' would not influence the output.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] This criterion requires that all combinations of conditions inside each decision are tested.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Safety-critical or dependable applications are often required to demonstrate 100% of some form of test coverage.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] For example, the ECSS-E-ST-40C standard demands 100% statement and decision coverage for two out of four different criticality levels; for the other ones, target coverage values are up to negotiation between supplier and customer.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Some of the coverage criteria above are connected.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] For instance, path coverage implies decision, statement and entry/exit coverage.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Decision coverage implies statement coverage, because every statement is part of a branch.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Full path coverage, of the type described above, is usually impractical or impossible.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Any module with a succession of n decisions in it can have up to $2^{n}$ paths within it; loop constructs can result in an infinite number of paths.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Many paths may also be infeasible, in that there is no input to the program under test that can cause that particular path to be executed.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] However, a general-purpose algorithm for identifying infeasible paths has been proven to be impossible (such an algorithm could be used to solve the halting problem).
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Basis path testing is for instance a method of achieving complete branch coverage without achieving complete path coverage.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Methods for practical path coverage testing instead attempt to identify classes of code paths that differ only in the number of loop executions, and to achieve "basis path" coverage the tester must cover all the path classes.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] The target software is built with special options or libraries and run under a controlled environment, to map every executed function to the function points in the source code.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] This allows testing parts of the target software that are rarely or never accessed under normal conditions, and helps reassure that the most important conditions (function points) have been tested.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] The resulting output is then analyzed to see what areas of code have not been exercised and the tests are updated to include these areas as necessary.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Combined with other test coverage methods, the aim is to develop a rigorous, yet manageable, set of regression tests.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Software authors can look at test coverage results to devise additional tests and input or configuration sets to increase the coverage over vital functions.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Two common forms of test coverage are statement (or line) coverage and branch (or edge) coverage.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Line coverage reports on the execution footprint of testing in terms of which lines of code were executed to complete the test.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Edge coverage reports which branches or code decision points were executed to complete the test.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] They both report a coverage metric, measured as a percentage.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] The meaning of this depends on what form(s) of coverage have been used, as 67% branch coverage is more comprehensive than 67% statement coverage.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Generally, test coverage tools incur computation and logging in addition to the actual program thereby slowing down the application, so typically this analysis is not done in production.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] As one might expect, there are classes of software that cannot be feasibly subjected to these coverage tests, though a degree of coverage mapping can be approximated through analysis rather than direct testing.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] There are also some sorts of defects which are affected by such tools.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] In particular, some race conditions or similar real time sensitive operations can be masked when run under test environments; though conversely, some of these defects may become easier to find as a result of the additional overhead of the testing code.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Most professional software developers use C1 and C2 coverage.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] C1 stands for statement coverage and C2 for branch or condition coverage.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] With a combination of C1 and C2, it is possible to cover most statements in a code base.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Statement coverage would also cover function coverage with entry and exit, loop, path, state flow, control flow and data flow coverage.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] With these methods, it is possible to achieve nearly 100% code coverage in most software projects.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Test coverage is one consideration in the safety certification of avionics equipment.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] The guidelines by which avionics gear is certified by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) is documented in DO-178B and DO-178C.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-coverage] Test coverage is also a requirement in part 6 of the automotive safety standard ISO 26262 *Road Vehicles - Functional Safety*.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Code review differs from related software quality assurance techniques like static code analysis, self-checks, testing, and pair programming.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Static analysis relies primarily on automated tools, self-checks involve only the author, testing requires code execution, and pair programming is performed continuously during development rather than as a separate step.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Several variations of code review processes exist, with additional types specified in IEEE 1028.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] The first code review process that was studied and described in detail was called "Inspection" by its inventor, Michael Fagan.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Fagan inspection is a formal process that involves a careful and detailed execution with multiple participants and phases.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] In formal code reviews, software developers attend a series of meetings to examine code line by line, often using printed copies.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Research has shown formal inspections to be extremely thorough and highly effective at identifying defects.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Software development teams typically adopt a more lightweight review process in which the scope of each review relates to changes to the codebase corresponding to a ticket, user story, commit, or some other unit of work.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Furthermore, there are rules or conventions that integrate the review task into the development workflow through conventions like mandatory review of all tickets, commonly as part of a pull request, instead of explicitly planning each review.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Such a process is called "regular, change-based code review".
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] There are many variations of this basic process.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] A 2017 survey of 240 development teams found that 90% of teams using code review followed a change-based process, with 60% specifically using regular change-based review.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Major software corporations known to use changed-based code review include Microsoft, Google, and Facebook.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Ongoing research by Capers Jones analyzing over 12,000 software development projects found formal inspections had a latent defect discovery rate of 60-65%, while informal inspections detected fewer than 50% of defects.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] The latent defect discovery rate for most forms of testing is about 30%.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] A code review case study published in the book *Best Kept Secrets of Peer Code Review* contradicted the Capers Jones study, finding that lightweight reviews can uncover as many bugs as formal reviews while being faster and less costly.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Studies indicate that up to 75% of code review comments affect software evolvability and maintainability rather than functionality, suggesting that code reviews are an excellent tool for software companies with long product or system life cycles.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Therefore, less than 15% of issues discussed in code reviews relate directly to bugs.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Research indicates review effectiveness correlates with review speed.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Optimal code review rates range from 200 to 400 lines of code per hour.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Inspecting and reviewing more than a few hundred lines of code per hour for critical software (such as safety critical embedded software) may be too fast to find errors.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] Static code analysis tools assist reviewers by automatically checking source code for known vulnerabilities and defect patterns, particularly for large chunks of code.
[src:secure-coding-practices/code-review] A 2012 study by VDC Research reports that 17.6% of the embedded software engineers surveyed currently use automated tools to support peer code review and 23.7% plan to use them within two years.
[src:secure-coding-practices/common-weakness-enumeration] The **Common Weakness Enumeration** (**CWE**) is a category system for hardware and software weaknesses and vulnerabilities.
[src:secure-coding-practices/common-weakness-enumeration] It is sustained by a community project with the goals of understanding flaws in software and hardware and creating automated tools that can be used to identify, fix, and prevent those flaws.
[src:secure-coding-practices/common-weakness-enumeration] The project is sponsored by the office of the U.S.
[src:secure-coding-practices/common-weakness-enumeration] Department of Homeland Security (DHS) Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA), which is operated by The MITRE Corporation, with support from US-CERT and the National Cyber Security Division of the U.S.
[src:secure-coding-practices/common-weakness-enumeration] The first release of the list and associated classification taxonomy was in 2006.
[src:secure-coding-practices/common-weakness-enumeration] Version 4.15 of the CWE standard was released in July 2024.
[src:secure-coding-practices/common-weakness-enumeration] CWE has over 600 categories, including classes for buffer overflows, path/directory tree traversal errors, race conditions, cross-site scripting, hard-coded passwords, and insecure random numbers.
[src:secure-coding-practices/common-weakness-enumeration] Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE) Compatibility program allows a service or a product to be reviewed and registered as officially "CWE-Compatible" and "CWE-Effective".
[src:secure-coding-practices/common-weakness-enumeration] The program assists organizations in selecting the right software tools and learning about possible weaknesses and their possible impact.
[src:secure-coding-practices/common-weakness-enumeration] There are 56 organizations as of September 2019 that develop and maintain products and services that achieved CWE Compatible status.
[src:secure-coding-practices/common-weakness-enumeration] Some researchers think that ambiguities in CWE can be avoided or reduced.
[src:secure-coding-practices/common-weakness-enumeration] As of 4/16/2024, the CWE Compatibility Program has been discontinued.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] On the other side, a DAST tool is a program which communicates with a web application through the web front-end in order to identify potential security vulnerabilities in the web application and architectural weaknesses.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] Unlike static application security testing tools, DAST tools do not have access to the source code and therefore detect vulnerabilities by actually performing attacks.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] DAST tools allow sophisticated scans, detecting vulnerabilities with minimal user interactions once configured with host name, crawling parameters and authentication credentials.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] These tools will attempt to detect vulnerabilities in query strings, headers, fragments, verbs (GET/POST/PUT) and DOM injection.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] DAST tools facilitate the automated review of a web application with the express purpose of discovering security vulnerabilities and are required to comply with various regulatory requirements.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] Web application scanners can look for a wide variety of vulnerabilities, such as input/output validation: (e.g. cross-site scripting and SQL injection), specific application problems and server configuration mistakes.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] Commercial scanners are a category of web-assessment tools which need to be purchased.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] Some scanners include some free features but most need to be bought for full access to the tool's power.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] Open-source scanners are often free of cost to the user.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] These tools can detect vulnerabilities of the finalized release candidate versions prior to shipping.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] Scanners simulate a malicious user by attacking and probing, identifying results which are not part of the expected result set, allowing for a realistic attack simulation.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] The big advantage of these types of tools are that they can scan year-round to be constantly searching for vulnerabilities.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] With new vulnerabilities being discovered regularly this allows companies to find and patch vulnerabilities before they can become exploited.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] As a dynamic testing tool, web scanners are not language-dependent.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] A web application scanner is able to scan engine-driven web applications.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] Attackers use the same tools, so if the tools can find a vulnerability, so can attackers.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] While scanning with a DAST tool, data may be overwritten or malicious payloads injected into the subject site.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] Sites should be scanned in a production-like but non-production environment to ensure accurate results while protecting the data in the production environment.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] Because the tool is implementing a dynamic testing method, it cannot cover 100% of the source code of the application and then, the application itself.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] The penetration tester should look at the coverage of the web application or of its attack surface to know if the tool was configured correctly or was able to understand the web application.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] The tool cannot implement all variants of attacks for a given vulnerability.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] So the tools generally have a predefined list of attacks and do not generate the attack payloads depending on the tested web application.
[src:secure-coding-practices/dynamic-application-security-testing] Some tools are also quite limited in their understanding of the behavior of applications with dynamic content such as JavaScript and Flash.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] In computing, **data validation** or **input validation** is the process of ensuring data has undergone data cleansing to confirm it has data quality, that is, that it is both correct and useful.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] It uses routines, often called "validation rules", "validation constraints", or "check routines", that check for correctness, meaningfulness, and security of data that are input to the system.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] The rules may be implemented through the automated facilities of a data dictionary, or by the inclusion of explicit application program validation logic of the computer and its application.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] This is distinct from formal verification, which attempts to prove or disprove the correctness of algorithms for implementing a specification or property.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Data validation is intended to provide certain well-defined guarantees for fitness and consistency of data in an application or automated system.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Data validation rules can be defined and designed using various methodologies, and be deployed in various contexts.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Their implementation can use declarative data integrity rules, or procedure-based business rules.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] The guarantees of data validation do not necessarily include accuracy, and it is possible for data entry errors such as misspellings to be accepted as valid.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Other clerical and/or computer controls may be applied to reduce inaccuracy within a system.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] In evaluating the basics of data validation, generalizations can be made regarding the different kinds of validation according to their scope, complexity, and purpose.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Data type validation is customarily carried out on one or more simple data fields.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] The simplest kind of data type validation verifies that the individual characters provided through user input are consistent with the expected characters of one or more known primitive data types as defined in a programming language or data storage and retrieval mechanism.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] For example, an integer field may require input to use only characters 0 through 9.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Simple range and constraint validation may examine input for consistency with a minimum/maximum range, or consistency with a test for evaluating a sequence of characters, such as one or more tests against regular expressions.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] For example, a counter value may be required to be a non-negative integer, and a password may be required to meet a minimum length and contain characters from multiple categories.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Code and cross-reference validation includes operations to verify that data is consistent with one or more possibly-external rules, requirements, or collections relevant to a particular organization, context or set of underlying assumptions.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] These additional validity constraints may involve cross-referencing supplied data with a known look-up table or directory information service such as LDAP.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] For example, a user-provided country code might be required to identify a current geopolitical region.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Structured validation allows for the combination of other kinds of validation, along with more complex processing.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Such complex processing may include the testing of conditional constraints for an entire complex data object or set of process operations within a system.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Consistency validation ensures that data is logical.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] For example, the delivery date of an order can be prohibited from preceding its shipment date.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Multiple kinds of data validation are relevant to 10-digit pre-2007 ISBNs (the 2005 edition of ISO 2108 required ISBNs to have 13 digits from 2007 onwards).
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Checks to ascertain that only expected characters are present in a field.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] For example a numeric field may only allow the digits 0–9, the decimal point and perhaps a minus sign or commas.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] An e-mail address might require at least one @ sign and various other structural details.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] can be effective ways to implement such checks.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Numerical fields may be added together for all records in a batch.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] The batch total is entered and the computer checks that the total is correct, e.g., add the 'Total Cost' field of a number of transactions together.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Checks that record has a valid number of related records.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] For example, if a contact record is classified as "customer" then it must have at least one associated order (cardinality > 0).
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] This type of rule can be complicated by additional conditions.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] For example, if a contact record in a payroll database is classified as "former employee" then it must not have any associated salary payments after the separation date (cardinality = 0).
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] To support error detection, an extra digit is added to a number which is calculated from the other digits.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Checks fields to ensure data in these fields correspond, e.g., if expiration date is in the past then status is not "active".
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Compares data in different systems to ensure it is consistent.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Systems may represent the same data differently, in which case comparison requires transformation (e.g., one system may store customer name in a single Name field as 'Doe, John Q', while another uses First_Name 'John' and Last_Name 'Doe' and Middle_Name 'Quality').
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Checks input conformance with typed data.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] For example, an input box accepting numeric data may reject the letter 'O'.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Checks that a file with a specified name exists.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] This check is essential for programs that use file handling.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Checks that the data is in a specified format (template), e.g., dates have to be in the format YYYY-MM-DD.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Regular expressions may be used for this kind of validation.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Checks that data is present, e.g., customers may be required to have an email address.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Checks that the data is within a specified range of values, e.g., a probability must be between 0 and 1.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] tables can be linked through foreign key and primary key.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] If values in the foreign key field are not constrained by internal mechanisms, then they should be validated to ensure that the referencing table always refers to a row in the referenced table.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Looks for spelling and grammatical errors.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] This can be applied to several fields (i.e.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] A table look up check compares data to a collection of allowed values.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Enforcement action typically rejects the data entry request and requires the input actor to make a change that brings the data into compliance.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] This is most suitable for interactive use, where a real person is sitting on the computer and making entry.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] It also works well for batch upload, where a file input may be rejected and a set of messages sent back to the input source for why the data is rejected.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Another form of enforcement action involves automatically changing the data and saving a conformant version instead of the original version.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] This is most suitable for cosmetic change.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] For example, converting an [all-caps] entry to a [Pascal case] entry does not need user input.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] An inappropriate use of automatic enforcement would be in situations where the enforcement leads to loss of business information.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] For example, saving a truncated comment if the length is longer than expected.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] This is not typically a good thing since it may result in loss of significant data.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Advisory actions typically allow data to be entered unchanged but sends a message to the source actor indicating those validation issues that were encountered.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] This is most suitable for non-interactive system, for systems where the change is not business critical, for cleansing steps of existing data and for verification steps of an entry process.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Verification actions are special cases of advisory actions.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] In this case, the source actor is asked to verify that this data is what they would really want to enter, in the light of a suggestion to the contrary.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Here, the check step suggests an alternative (e.g., a check of a mailing address returns a different way of formatting that address or suggests a different address altogether).
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] You would want in this case, to give the user the option of accepting the recommendation or keeping their version.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] This is not a strict validation process, by design and is useful for capturing addresses to a new location or to a location that is not yet supported by the validation databases.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Even in cases where data validation did not find any issues, providing a log of validations that were conducted and their results is important.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Failures or omissions in data validation can lead to data corruption or a security vulnerability.
[src:secure-coding-practices/input-validation] Data validation checks that data are fit for purpose, valid, sensible, reasonable and secure before they are processed.
[src:secure-coding-practices/secure-by-design] Assuming that systems will be attacked, secure by design entails limiting their architecture to make compromises challenging, contained, and recoverable.
[src:secure-coding-practices/secure-by-design] It highlights strategies like defence in depth, minimising attack surfaces, the principle of least privilege principle, and integrating detection and response mechanisms.
[src:secure-coding-practices/secure-by-design] SbD treats security as a design constraint on par with performance, usability, and cost, in contrast to reactive approaches that mainly rely on vulnerability management after deployment.
[src:secure-coding-practices/secure-by-design] Since significant cyber events, such as supply chain breaches and ransomware campaigns, have shown the shortcomings of reactive security, secure by design has gained popularity in the twenty-first century.
[src:secure-coding-practices/secure-by-design] SbD practices are now more frequently required by governments, businesses, and standards organisations in a variety of domains, from consumer Internet of Things (IoT) devices to defence systems.
[src:secure-coding-practices/secure-by-design] There are similarities between the idea and related paradigms like safety by design, privacy by design, and the larger trend towards resilient systems engineering.
[src:secure-coding-practices/secure-by-design] These ideas complement and overlap with related paradigms like safety by design, privacy by design, and zero trust architecture (ZTA).
[src:secure-coding-practices/secure-by-design] Secure by design is a design philosophy that can be used in different development lifecycles, such as Agile, Waterfall, and DevSecOps.
[src:secure-coding-practices/secure-by-design] While widely endorsed, Secure by Design faces challenges in practice.
[src:secure-coding-practices/secure-by-design] Early investment in security design may increase upfront costs, although the reduction in risk provides long-term benefits.
[src:secure-coding-practices/secure-by-design] Applying SbD to legacy systems with older architectures is often impractical.
[src:secure-coding-practices/secure-by-design] Reliance on complex software supply chains with third-party software and components may undermine SbD practices.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Unlike dynamic application security testing (DAST) tools for black-box testing of application functionality, SAST tools focus on the code content of the application, white-box testing.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] A SAST tool scans the source code of applications and their components to identify potential security vulnerabilities in their software and architecture.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Static analysis tools can detect an estimated 50% of existing security vulnerabilities in tested applications.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] In the software development life cycle (SDLC), SAST is performed early in the development process and at code level, and also when all pieces of code and components are put together in a consistent testing environment.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] SAST is also used for software quality assurance, even if the many resulting false positives impede its adoption by developers.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] SAST tools are integrated into the development process to help development teams as they are primarily focusing on developing and delivering software respecting requested specifications.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] SAST tools, like other security tools, focus on reducing the risk of downtime of applications or that private information stored in applications is not compromised.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Application security tests conducted before their release include static application security testing (SAST), dynamic application security testing (DAST), and interactive application security testing (IAST), which is a combination of the two.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Static analysis tools examine the text of a program syntactically.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] They look for a fixed set of patterns or rules in the source code.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Theoretically, they can also examine a compiled form of the software.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] This technique relies on instrumentation of the code to do the mapping between compiled components and source code components to identify issues.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Static analysis can be done manually as a code review or auditing of the code for different purposes, including security, but it is time-consuming.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] The precision of SAST tools is determined by their scope of analysis and the specific techniques used to identify vulnerabilities.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] The scope of the analysis determines its accuracy and capacity to detect vulnerabilities using contextual information.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] SAST tools, unlike DAST tools, give developers real-time feedback, and help them secure flaws before they move the code to the next level.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] At a function level, a common technique is the construction of an Abstract syntax tree to control the flow of data within the function.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Since the late 90s, the need to adapt to business challenges has transformed software development with componentization enforced by processes and organization of development teams.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Following the flow of data between all the components of an application or group of applications allows validation of required calls to dedicated procedures for sanitization and that proper actions are taken to taint data in specific pieces of code.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] The rise of web applications entailed testing them: Verizon Data Breach reported in 2016 that 40% of all data breaches use web application vulnerabilities.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Both external security validations and a focus on internal threats have risen.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] The Clearswift Insider Threat Index (CITI) has reported that 92% of their respondents in a 2015 survey said they had experienced IT or security incidents in the previous 12 months and that 74% of these breaches were originated by insiders.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Lee Hadlington categorized internal threats in 3 categories: malicious, accidental, and unintentional.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Mobile applications' explosive growth implies securing applications earlier in the development process to reduce malicious code development.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] The earlier a vulnerability is fixed in the SDLC, the cheaper it is to fix.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Costs to fix in development are 10 times lower than in testing, and 100 times lower than in production.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] SAST tools run automatically, either at the code level or application-level and do not require interaction.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] When integrated into a CI/CD context, SAST tools can be used to automatically stop the integration process if critical vulnerabilities are identified.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Another advantage over other types of testing is that SAST tools scan the entire source code, while dynamic application security testing tools cover its execution, possibly missing part of the application or unsecured configuration in configuration files.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] SAST tools can offer extended functionalities such as quality and architectural testing.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] There is a direct correlation between software quality and security.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Bad quality software is also poorly secured software.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Even though developers are positive about the usage of SAST tools, there are different challenges to their adoption.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] As an example, research shows that despite the long output generated by these tools, they may lack usability.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] With Agile Processes in software development, early integration of SAST generates many bugs, as developers using this framework focus first on features and delivery.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] Scanning many lines of code with SAST tools may result in hundreds or thousands of vulnerability warnings for a single application.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] It can generate many false positives, increasing investigation time and reducing trust in such tools.
[src:secure-coding-practices/static-application-security-testing] This is particularly the case when the context of the vulnerability cannot be caught by the tool.
